<subSubSection id="A5050F33A5FE7BE3E51DBE2DBF77C17F" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="DC059AE6F08613084A10F16336581A6E" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D2B9CA45AFFF8FD2B37A9833C79C7A81" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName id="3E532085461EEC93DDF996BA3D18DF51" authorityName="G. Q. Hao, J. Quan Liu &amp; Al-Shehbaz" authorityYear="2018" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Eutrema" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Eutrema nanum" order="Brassicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nanum">
<emphasis id="183A7969C56C22BF9D0B2D811E35D6A9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Eutrema nanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently known only from Chola Shan, part of Hengduan Mountains in West Sichuan, China (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="05EC00653492BDC4A0050ED9C6CC19BE" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Geographical distribution of the sampled populations of Eutrema nanum and related species." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.109.27049.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/228467" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">3</figureCitation>
). It grows under rocks by streams close to glaciers, damp or gravelly scree, wet sand at a very high elevation of 4500-4600 m.
</paragraph>
<caption id="47940E0F0B295690C202F23BF21B9A1A" ID-Zenodo-Dep="1434558" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.109.27049.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/228467" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
